Observation Details: Rare for this date and location. Empid with gray-olive head, mantle and back, grey cheeks, light gray throat, grayish green chest and belly, whitish vent. Narrow short bill, black on top, black tipped fading to dull orange on bottom. Medium primary projection. Two prominent white wing bars. Blocky head shape. White eye ring with tear shape to the rear of the eye. Silent. Feeding and perching low, landing on the ground several times. Seen not far from where the Palm Warbler was seen (scrub area south of the playground area). 37.912754, -122.386627 Please see photos.
Continuing bird reported by Derek Heinz. In area noted by Derek.

[Update entry to RTHU based on input from Sheri Williamson on 9/1: "It's a juvenile male Ruby-throated. The mask is darker than usual in juvenile male Black-chinneds, and the tail notch is quite deep, exposing the black tips of R3-4, and the third photo shows the diagnostic elongated oval tip on P5 and the sharply pointed P6."]  This appears to be either a Black-chinned or Ruby-throated Hummingbird, the two species in the genus Archilochus. BCHU is rare for this location. RTHU is very rare for the state of California with no accepted records in Alameda County. I believe the totality of the field marks point to RTHU, but am entering as BCHU/RTHU as I seek out further opinions and research further.  I first noted the presence of a hummingbird that seemed smaller than the expected Anna’s near a flowering shrub in the wooded area of Cesar Chavez park. After some 15 minutes a hummingbird appeared that seemed different to the naked eye with a sort of white collar extending above the shoulder. It landed and I took some images. The bird was silent. It then flew off and was not seen again for the following 20 minutes. From the images I note dark, contrasting auriculars, a white spot limited to just behind the eye, green back with golden hues, greyish crown, forked tail with white tips to the rectrices, lightly marked white throat, stout straight-ish, medium length bill. Some of these characters are good for a female type Black-chinned Hummingbird, whereas all of them support Ruby-throated Hummingbird, and, in the aggregate, are not good for the other likely hummingbirds for the area.  I will go through and attempt to eliminate the non-Archilochus hummingbirds in order of likelihood. In all cases I am considering female/juvenile of the species:  Anna’s Hummingbird - By far the most likely hummingbird species in this location, and anywhere in the county at this time of the year, is ANHU. The bird in question had a forked tail when at rest. This is not noted in ANHU and this feature alone can rule out ANHU. However, there are other marks against ANHU: The post-ocular white is limited to the area behind the eye - In ANHU the white should wrap over the top of the eye; buff color on flanks and around legs - ANHU lacks buff coloration; the throat is white with light marking - an adult female ANHU typically shows a dark spot in the throat area. Juvenile ANHU typically has an unmarked throat, but a juvenile ANHU would not likely have a bill as stout and long as this bird. I believe the totality of these marks safely rules out ANHU.  Rufous/Allen's Hummingbird - The bird in question lacks rufous and cannot be RUHU or ALHU.   Costa’s Hummingbird - The stoutness and length of the bill, and darkness of the auriculars can rule out Costa’s, among other features noted in the ANHU section above.  Calliope Hummingbird - Lack of extensive buffiness in sides of chest as well as stoutness and length of bill rule out Calliope.  Black-chinned Hummingbird - The auriculars are dark, prominent and very contrasty. In BCHU the auriculars tend grayer, less prominent, less contrasty. These dark auriculars would be unusual in BCHU. The forehead appears grayish, a mark in favor of BCHU, but does not rule out RTHU. The wingtips appear to not reach the tip of the tail as expected in BCHU. The wingtips do not appear to show a broadening or curving at the tips as expected in BCHU. The bill is of medium length and in some angles has a slight curve to it. It is perhaps not conclusive in separating BCHU and RTHU, but the bill seems typical for RTHU and does not seem typical of BCHU, which, if adult, should be longer and more distinctly down-curved.

Seen in two places up in the hills. First sighting in the pines to the north of the Crest Trail Circle. I left this bird feeding in the conifers and proceeded down to the north along the Crest Trail. Second sighting occurred in the Crest Trail saddle to the north five minutes later. I was about to head up to the knob when I heard a Townshend-like chip note (distinctly similar to the chips I just heard from the first bird). This second bird was back in some lower deciduous growth and I decided to wait it out. Eventually a HEWA popped out in the open on a bare branch for brief views. Chips continued for awhile. It's conceivable that they are the same bird but much more likely that there are two, given the time frame. Pictures are of the first sighting.

Continuing Frank’s Dump. Photos.

Best estimate. (I'm not trying to undercount to make sure the estimate is "conservative", I'm making my best estimate. However, as a rule, I don't count already assessed birds on my return trip, and I try to limit potential for double counting in general.) Regularly seen and heard, mainly along Old San Pablo Road. Immediately upon arrival had 5 in in a few minutes in the main parking area.

Small Cooper's. Perhaps the same individual that buzzed me (near the start of my walk) on its attack on a large sparrow flock. It used me as cover and I only had very brief looks. I noticed birds scattering, then "phoomph" as it passed me in their direction. When I saw the bird reported here (at the end of my walk) it flew in and landed high in a pine in a perfect vantage point for such an attack. I thought the attacking bird had to be a Merlin or Sharp-shinned, due to size.

Recent local escape/release, or from population in the southbay or more robust Southern CA population? Unmistakable bright orange and black male. About house finch size. Black face, eyes and bill, belly and wings (feathers on wing and a whitish edging). Orange nape, throat, back and tail. The orange nape puffed up a couple times creating a collar effect similar to a Bobolink's sometimes puffy cream-colored nape. First alerted to it by call (new to me) in the scrub area where it was initially low in thickets. It then flew up and perched, calling frequently. Eventually flew to top of eucalyptus where it appeared to be feeding, still calling. Will post recording later. 37.912845, -122.387111 (google maps)

Rare for this date and location. Empid with gray-olive head, mantle and back, grey cheeks, light gray throat, grayish green chest and belly, whitish vent. Narrow short bill, black on top, black tipped fading to dull orange on bottom. Medium primary projection. Two prominent white wing bars. Blocky head shape. White eye ring with tear shape to the rear of the eye. Silent. Feeding and perching low, landing on the ground several times. Seen not far from where the Palm Warbler was seen (scrub area south of the playground area). 37.912754, -122.386627 Please see photos.

First found by Logan Kahle yesterday. Large warbler, Song Sparrow sized. Muddy-brown back, tail and cap (thrush-like in this respect). Thick brown streaks covering buffy breast and flanks. Distinct, buffy supercilium that curves over and down behind eyes and reaching to the sides of the nape. Pink legs. Walking on banks secretively in the shadows yet comfortable out in the open. Pipit-like walk. Silent.

Initially reported as Baird's in the field. Distant views without scope, only binos. Medium-sized, squatty sandpiper, shorter and smaller than nearby killdeer, not much bigger than nearby starlings. Brown back, head and breast, distinct transition from brown breast to white belly and vent. In photos, legs longer than recalled, but are generally crouched. Don't recall good views of leg color. In flight, showed black line through white rump. Feeding in mud in south pond. Medium-sized, nape-to-nare lengthed bill. Need to review photos. Photos, while of poor quality, are good for Pectoral.

[Update entry to RTHU based on input from Sheri Williamson on 9/1: "It's a juvenile male Ruby-throated. The mask is darker than usual in juvenile male Black-chinneds, and the tail notch is quite deep, exposing the black tips of R3-4, and the third photo shows the diagnostic elongated oval tip on P5 and the sharply pointed P6."]  This appears to be either a Black-chinned or Ruby-throated Hummingbird, the two species in the genus Archilochus. BCHU is rare for this location. RTHU is very rare for the state of California with no accepted records in Alameda County. I believe the totality of the field marks point to RTHU, but am entering as BCHU/RTHU as I seek out further opinions and research further.  I first noted the presence of a hummingbird that seemed smaller than the expected Anna’s near a flowering shrub in the wooded area of Cesar Chavez park. After some 15 minutes a hummingbird appeared that seemed different to the naked eye with a sort of white collar extending above the shoulder. It landed and I took some images. The bird was silent. It then flew off and was not seen again for the following 20 minutes. From the images I note dark, contrasting auriculars, a white spot limited to just behind the eye, green back with golden hues, greyish crown, forked tail with white tips to the rectrices, lightly marked white throat, stout straight-ish, medium length bill. Some of these characters are good for a female type Black-chinned Hummingbird, whereas all of them support Ruby-throated Hummingbird, and, in the aggregate, are not good for the other likely hummingbirds for the area.  I will go through and attempt to eliminate the non-Archilochus hummingbirds in order of likelihood. In all cases I am considering female/juvenile of the species:  Anna’s Hummingbird - By far the most likely hummingbird species in this location, and anywhere in the county at this time of the year, is ANHU. The bird in question had a forked tail when at rest. This is not noted in ANHU and this feature alone can rule out ANHU. However, there are other marks against ANHU: The post-ocular white is limited to the area behind the eye - In ANHU the white should wrap over the top of the eye; buff color on flanks and around legs - ANHU lacks buff coloration; the throat is white with light marking - an adult female ANHU typically shows a dark spot in the throat area. Juvenile ANHU typically has an unmarked throat, but a juvenile ANHU would not likely have a bill as stout and long as this bird. I believe the totality of these marks safely rules out ANHU.  Rufous/Allen's Hummingbird - The bird in question lacks rufous and cannot be RUHU or ALHU.   Costa’s Hummingbird - The stoutness and length of the bill, and darkness of the auriculars can rule out Costa’s, among other features noted in the ANHU section above.  Calliope Hummingbird - Lack of extensive buffiness in sides of chest as well as stoutness and length of bill rule out Calliope.  Black-chinned Hummingbird - The auriculars are dark, prominent and very contrasty. In BCHU the auriculars tend grayer, less prominent, less contrasty. These dark auriculars would be unusual in BCHU. The forehead appears grayish, a mark in favor of BCHU, but does not rule out RTHU. The wingtips appear to not reach the tip of the tail as expected in BCHU. The wingtips do not appear to show a broadening or curving at the tips as expected in BCHU. The bill is of medium length and in some angles has a slight curve to it. It is perhaps not conclusive in separating BCHU and RTHU, but the bill seems typical for RTHU and does not seem typical of BCHU, which, if adult, should be longer and more distinctly down-curved.

Locality: Pt. Reyes--Nunes Ranch (A Ranch) & Road Forks Pool
Observation Details: Wing - feathers (see images no. 1 and 2). Although not conclusive, the outer four primaries appear broader than the inner six primaries. This character is only evident in Black-chinned and Ruby-throated and would rule out all other species.   Color of and lack of markings on throat, breast and flanks (see all photographs). The entire area of the throat, breast and flanks are a clean white, contrasting with the green back. This eliminates Anna's which typically has a green, buffy flank and spotting on the central throat. While there can be variation in these features, it would be anomalous for an Anna's to so thoroughly lack these characters. Black-chinned perhaps cannot be decisively ruled out here but they typically have gray buffy to the flanks and some light spotting to the whitish throat. On the other hand a clean white throat, breast and flank contrasting distinctly with the back and face are more promising features for a female Ruby-throated.   Bill shape and length (see all images). The bill is straight with a length aproximately the width of the head, from nape to nare. Black-chinned typically have a decurved bill that averages longer than the width of the head. A juvenile Black-chinned might have this bill, so juvenile Black-chinned must be considered and ruled out elsewhere. Costa's, which have a decurved, finer bill, can be ruled out. The shape and length of the bill are good for Ruby-throated.   Wing - shape and length (see images no. 1 and 2). Perhaps the best view of the shape of the wing is in image no. 2. It shows, on the right side of the body, a narrow wing that ends with a straight tip, which is expected for Ruby-throated. A Black-chinned wing tends to curve inward ending with a rounded, curved tip. The length of the wing is best determined in image no. 1 where the tip of the right wing appears slightly shorter than the tail, but this mark is not conclusive and within range of both Archilocus species.   Color of crown and lores (see all images). The crown shows green which is better for Ruby-crowned. The crown of a Black-chinned sends to be grayer, lacking green. The lore in this bird is dark black, a character that is not noted in Black-chinned, but is a strong mark for Ruby-throated. Moreover, the combination black lore and green crown contrast distinctly with the white throat, a feature to look for in Ruby-throated. The contrast is not good for Costa's which typically have a grey cheek patch extending behind the eye.  Aging and Crown Color: Based on tail pattern, our bird can be confidently aged as a 1st-fall bird: It shows a weak but clearly present white tip on R2, which is characteristic of immature Archilochus and Calypte hummers and is absent on adults. Given that this is an immature bird, the green crown decisively rules out Black-chinned Hummingbird. According to Sheri L. Williamson's "Hummingbirds of North America," immature Black-chinned of both sexes have gray crowns, while immature Ruby-throated have green crowns. Our bird is an immature that shows a distinctly green crown, thus ruling out Black-chinned. Additionally, the tail pattern eliminates immature male Costa's, which should show no pale tip on R2 and only a very small one on R3, although immature females can have a similar tail pattern (see our discussions of face pattern and other features for elimination of Costa's).

See photos. Spectacled vireo with gray head and back, white wing bars. Rump not seen. White throat, belly and vent. A very light wash of yellow on edges of vent. Each evening Orchard Orioles stage in tree and fly northwest overhead in easily counted groups of 15-30, probably in aggregate numbers significantly more than reported. My impression was at least 150, but subsequent observations with more focused counting yielded around 125 birds.
